# No method bypass

A **method bypass** is any method whose body only forwards the same arguments to another method and returns its result (possibly through a short chain). Do not add bypasses; call the target directly.

```java
// ❌ Bypass — same parameters, no added behavior
public static String url(Tag tag) {
    return TagPaths.url(tag);
}

// ✅ Call the implementation
TagPaths.url(tag);
```

Bypass chains compound the problem: `A.foo(x)` → `B.foo(x)` → `C.foo(x)`.

## When a wrapper is allowed

Keep a method only when it **adds** something the callee does not: validation, authorization, caching, mapping to a different type, framework contract (e.g. JAX-RS handler), or a stable public API that intentionally hides an internal type.

If the wrapper only exists for naming convenience or “closer to the caller,” delete it and update callers.

## When touching legacy bypasses

If you edit code that calls a bypass, switch to the canonical method in the same change. Remove the bypass once nothing references it.

## Example in this codebase — URL paths

Public route strings live in `*Paths` classes (`TagPaths`, `PostPaths`, `BlogPaths`, …). Endpoint statics that delegate to them are bypasses:

| Bypass | Call instead |
|--------|----------------|
| `TagPageEndpoint.url(tag)` | `TagPaths.url(tag)` |
| `PostEndpoint.extractUrl(post)` | `PostPaths.extractUrl(post)` |
| `BlogEndpoint.extractUrl(blog)` | `BlogPaths.extractUrl(blog)` |
| `SeriePageEndpoint.extractUrl(serie)` | `SeriePaths.extractUrl(serie)` |
| `AuthorProfileEndpoint.url(author)` | `AuthorProfilePaths.url(author)` |

`TemplateExtensions.url(entity)` is fine as the Qute entry point only if it delegates straight to `*Paths`, not through an endpoint static.

## Never

- Add a new method whose body is only `return Other.method(sameArgs)`.
- Route callers through a bypass “for consistency” when the canonical method is already public.
